---
import CaseStudyLayout from "../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import { weatherapp } from "../utils/images";

const sidebarItems = [
  { text: "Overview", href: "#overview" },
  { text: "Context", href: "#context" },
  { text: "Retrospective", href: "#retrospective" },
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  title="Weather GPT"
  subtitle="AI-Powered Weather Summaries - July 2024"
  pageTitle="Weather GPT - Liam Sullivan"
  sidebarItems={sidebarItems}
  projectRole={["Full-Stack Development", "API Integration"]}
  team={["Solo"]}
  tools={["Node.js", "Express", "EJS", "Tailwind", "OpenAI API"]}
  timeline={["1 Week"]}
  githubLink="https://github.com/liambsulliva/weather-app"
  demoLink="https://weather.liambsullivan.com/"
>
  <Image
    src={weatherapp}
    alt="Weather GPT"
    class="mx-auto max-h-[700px] w-auto rounded-xl"
    loading="eager"
    slot="hero"
  />

  <div class="case-study-layout">
    <section class="pb-10 pt-10 md:flex md:gap-20" id="overview">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Overview</h3>
      <div>
        <p>
          Weather GPT is a weather application that combines real-time weather
          data from the OpenWeather API with GPT-3.5's natural language
          processing capabilities. Instead of presenting raw weather data, the
          app generates human-readable summaries that explain current
          conditions, forecasts, and what to expect throughout the day.
        </p>
        <br />
        <p>
          The project explores the intersection of traditional API data and
          AI-powered interpretation, creating a more accessible and
          conversational weather experience.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="context">
      <h3 class="!mb-3 text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Context</h3>
      <p>
        This project was built as an exploration of integrating AI capabilities
        into a traditional web application. While weather apps are ubiquitous,
        they often present data in technical formats that require
        interpretation. I wanted to create something that could explain weather
        conditions in natural language, similar to how a local meteorologist
        might describe the day's forecast.
      </p>
      <br />
      <p>
        The architecture uses Node.js and Express to create a backend server
        that handles both API requests and server-side rendering. When a user
        searches for a location, the server:
      </p>
      <br />
      <ul>
        <li>
          Queries the OpenWeather API for current conditions and forecast data
        </li>
        <li>
          Sends the structured weather data to GPT-3.5 with a carefully crafted
          prompt
        </li>
        <li>
          Receives a natural language summary that contextualizes the data for
          the user
        </li>
        <li>
          Generates the HTML page dynamically using EJS templates, combining the
          raw data visualizations with AI-generated insights
        </li>
      </ul>
      <br />
      <p>
        EJS (Embedded JavaScript) was chosen as the templating engine for its
        simplicity and ability to generate dynamic HTML on the server. This
        approach means each weather query is rendered fresh with the latest
        data, and the AI summaries can adapt to specific weather conditions and
        patterns.
      </p>
      <br />
      <p>
        Tailwind CSS provides a clean, responsive interface that works across
        devices. The design prioritizes readability, ensuring both the visual
        weather data and the AI-generated text are easy to scan and understand
        at a glance.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="retrospective">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Retrospective</h3>
      <p>
        Building Weather GPT demonstrated how AI can enhance traditional web
        applications by adding a layer of interpretation and accessibility. The
        project successfully created a more human-friendly weather experience
        while maintaining technical accuracy.
      </p>
      <br />
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>AI as an Enhancement Layer:</strong> GPT-3.5 proved excellent at
          taking structured weather data and explaining it in conversational language.
          The key was crafting prompts that encouraged concise, practical summaries
          rather than verbose explanations.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Server-Side Processing:</strong> Handling the API calls and AI
          processing on the backend kept the client-side code simple and protected
          API keys. The server-side rendering approach with EJS meant fast initial
          page loads with no client-side JavaScript framework overhead.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Balancing Speed and Intelligence:</strong> Each weather request
          requires multiple API calls (OpenWeather + OpenAI), which adds latency.
          Implementing smart caching strategies helped reduce repeated calls for
          the same location within short time windows.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <br />
      <p><strong>Future Improvements</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Implement Redis caching to store recent weather summaries and reduce
          API costs
        </li>
        <li>
          Add support for severe weather alerts with AI-generated safety
          recommendations
        </li>
        <li>
          Create personalized summaries based on user preferences (e.g., runner,
          commuter, outdoor worker)
        </li>
        <li>
          Explore GPT-4 for more nuanced weather interpretations and
          context-aware suggestions
        </li>
        <li>Add location autocomplete to improve the search experience</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</CaseStudyLayout>
